gary danko. when i was going to college at uc berkeley, we read that gary danko was voted best restaurant in the nation (yep. that was our reaction. what?! in the nation?!). as a poor college student, my roommates and i could not afford to dine here. therefore, i decided to put it on my bucket list. for our two year anniversary, we thought we would take a chance and try to get a reservation! score! we got one! on a saturday! it could be that we were overhyped about this place... or because the restaurant was having a bad day. our experience at gary dank was somewhat of a letdown. we weren't greeted at all for 15 minutes, our server was barely around to answer any questions (because he was too busy attending to his other tables). when served, it was abrupt, very short and never with a smile. we felt bad just asking for more water. the meal was good but the bad service left a bad taste in our mouths. FOOD: food was good. we recommend the (i) risotto with lobster, rock shrimp, shimeji mushrooms, asparagus and peas (not pictured) and (ii) warm louisiana butter cake with apples, huckleberry sauce and vanilla bean ice cream. those were the two dishes that stood out from the rest. SERVICE: lackluster. didn't seem to want to serve us at all. AMBIENCE: dark. could be a nice date place. OVERALL: i wish we could say better things about this place but we would probably never come back. that's too bad given that they did win best restaurant of the year back in the day. for the price you pay for your meal, i would expect a lot more from gary danko... but that's just me.

I went to Gary Danko with a friend recently and was excited to see if it measured up to the hype. I had been wanting to check this place out ever since they came to give a tech talk at Google about superior service (as a countless-time award winner and establishment reputed as having the best service out of any restaurant in Northern California). With that being said, I think I'm going to get stampeded by a horde of angry Yelpers for giving Gary Danko less than 5 stars! Perhaps I just didn't order the "right" things, but I thought the food (while good) was not mindblowing, especially considering the price/quality ratio. Be prepared to spend a good amount of money here ($100+ per person). Things I Tried: Lobster Foie Gras Salad with Egg Wild Mushroom Stuffed Quail Macaroon with Ice Cream Dessert Nothing stood out to me as particularly spectacular, as I've had better versions of each elsewhere. Service was great, but also nothing spectacular. Perhaps my expectations were a bit too high, after hearing about feats performed here such as wait staff going next door to obtain a jacket for a lady who was cold or mythical heart-shaped meals created just for proposal dinners!

I am by no means new in knowing and understanding fine dining and how to judge it, so let me just lay it out flat for everyone who reads: Gary Danko is highly rated, and overrated. Unfortunately, they serve pretty amazing food. However, the service is tense, uncomfortable, and surprisingly inefficient despite the whole swarm of servers. The Coconut Thai Curry was sent back very apologetically because I did not read calamari on the menu and do not agree with it personally, and was received again without any calamari but with sand in the clams and shells as well. I hurt my tooth and chipped a piece of it off. Thanks for that. Furthermore, my boyfriend and I ordered the Creme Brûlée Trio and were severely disappointed. Maybe we have high standards for creme brûlée or maybe the creme brûlée at Cocotte is much better. *hint hint* (; The bottle of wine we paid $40 for is sold in stores for $13. Not to mention, the server dumped the sediment into my boyfriend's glass when we topped him off. Again, thanks. Enjoy the $300. We'll enjoy the better restaurants of San Francisco.

As good as advertised. Reservations can be hard to come by so plan them weeks, if not months, in advance (especially if you plan to go on the weekend). Obviously, if you come to Danko, be prepared to splurge. It's worth it though. If traveling by car, valet is available in front of the restaurant entrance on North Point or you can find street parking on any of the neighboring streets. The restaurant is small to medium sized and can seat 68 people at a given time. The main rooms can seat up to 6. There is a private room in the back that can seat up to 10. There are two private, spacious and well-decorated, unisex restrooms complete with soothing Indian sitar music. The interior of the restaurant is dark and can get a little loud when everyone's talking. There are many servers, all of whom are well-spoken and knowledgeable as to all the menu options and the ingredients and preparation behind them. They are all dressed in suits with Gary Danko lapel pins. All of them make you feel very welcome to dine here. The menu is prix fixe, but it is very flexible. You have a choice of three, four, or five course meals from a variety of categories including appetizers, fish and seafood, meat and game birds, cheese, and dessert. It's flexible because you can choose as many from each category as you'd like. So you can go with five appetizers or five dessert items if you want. They do ask that your party submit the entire order at one time so they get the timing of all your dishes and courses right. Also, the total amount of food served is the same, no matter if you order the three course or the five course. This means that portion sizes of each course are adjusted accordingly. Among the items ordered when we went (be sure to check out my Local Photos for pictures of most of the items listed below): Asparagus salad with quail eggs, prosciutto and red-onion caper vinaigrette. Dungeness crab salad with avocado mousse, pineapple, hearts of palm and curry-lemon vinaigrette. Lobster and fennel bisque with dungeness crab, peppers and saffron-orange remoulade. Glazed oysters with Osetra caviar, zucchini pearls and lettuce cream. Prosciutto wrapped bluenose bass with lentils, parsley, royal trumpet mushrooms, and fava beans. Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, carrot-ginger puree and vanilla poached rhubarb. Braised lamb shoulder and herb crusted loin with barley stew, red pepper relish and cumin yogurt. Quail stuffed with foie gras, mushrooms and quinoa, artichokes, olives and scallion-potato cake. Flambeed pineapple with coconut-macadamia dacquoise and rum-coconut sorbet prepared tableside. Strawberry dumplings with braised rhubarb and creme fraiche ice cream. Baked chocolate souffle with two sauces. There was also an amuse-bouche of spring onion bisque with a bread dumpling to start. At the end of the meal, the dessert also came along with a sample of various sweet dessert bites and a take-home pineapple and blueberry cheese breakfast cake (for ladies only). Very nice. All of the food was superb and lived up to the billing. There were a lot of nice touches to the dinner. For example, the bowl for the lobster and fennel bisque was pre-heated and the bisque was poured out of a small pot into the bowl at the table. The flambeed pineapple was also fun to watch being prepared tableside as you could see the sugar and cream being caramelized right in front of your eyes. Overall, Gary Danko was a great fine dining experience and I highly recommend it!

I don't consider myself particularly luckier than the average person in most regards. But one way in which I have extraordinary luck is food: I have eaten at some of the best eateries in existence, on the planet. In one way, this makes my reviews more diverse and accurate. In another way, this makes a 5-star rating from me impossible to attain. The last two reviews have been about birthday dinners for me. Number 3 was a place where we basically pay the rent, Shabu House. For #4 - enter Gary Danko (herein referred to as "GD"). This iconic establishment in San Francisco is constantly mentioned in the same sentence as the well-known French Laundry - people always preferring one over the other. Having frequented Thomas Keller's restaurants often - I was excited to try Gary Danko, where Rob had secured reservations for my actual birthdate evening. I was curious which I would end up preferring. Furthermore, GD was going to be compared to MY favorite SF dining establishment - Acquerello, as well. We arrived right on time, and the hostess asked if we had a reservation. Rob pointed to his name on the book, and we both noticed she immediately covered up the book - as if we were going to just point to a name and be seated, somehow omniscient to the fact that this particular party wouldn't show up in 2 minutes to boot us out? It was rude and inappropriate. However, she didn't ask for I.D. and seated us immediately. First, I was taken aback by how large the restaurant is. The ambiance is warm and very inviting, and the seating is very comfortable. With plenty of people waiting near the bar in hopes of being seated, plenty more were seated at the bar eating dinner there. Our server approached us, explained their menu, and asked if we'd like to start with drinks. We ordered a half bottle of champagne, because we knew we'd be doing the wine pairing for dinner. Rob ordered an ounce of the caviar ($125) to go w/ the champagne, which was excellent - great crème fraiche with the world's best bellinis - so full of butter I could FEEL myself gaining weight with each bite. Both of us opted for 5 courses. What stood out about the GD menu is that one can pick all five courses from any section. If you pick 5 main entrees, they will adjust portioning accordingly and serve it to you - or you could pick 5 desserts, for all they care. FL has a set menu, and Acquerello, you can pick one from each designated course. As usual, I have uploaded photos of the dinner courses. Rob opted for individual five courses, I chose the 5-course Summer Tasting Menu. After an amuse bouche - the meal began. Course 1: Ahi Tuna (Rob's) and Oysters w/ Caviar (mine, from the Summer Menu) - excellent wine pairing, with sake for the tuna. - I consider seared Ahi to be boring. Now I know that even Gary himself cannot do much to make this fish interesting. - LET IT BE SAID: THIS WAS THE FINEST OYSTER APPETIZER I HAVE EVER HAD IN MY ENTIRE LIFE. (Specifically, my comment was: "Move over, Thomas - I think I just fell in love w/ Gary Danko.") Course 2: Lobster Salad and Crusted Salmon - excellent wine pairing. - The lobster was good overall, but I have had better. I didn't think the dish itself was very flavorful. - LET IT BE SAID: THIS WAS THE BEST SALMON CREATION EVER. More than the salmon itself, how the flavors in this dish - the fish, the cucumbers, the horseradish, sauce, crust - was simply invigorating. (I envisioned Acquerello, sinking before my eyes....) Course 3: Pork Loin and Belly - Beef Filet - mediocre wine pairing. *This, along with the hostess episode, is where Gary Danko begins to remind me of the Titanic.* - Pork was unimpressive all around. The pork loin was dry and weak in taste, the pork belly was unremarkable in every way. (How does one ruin pork belly?) - Beef Filet - the meat was of excellent quality, it was a tad overcooked than I would have liked for this cut of meat, and the flavor of the meat ended up being masked by the sauces instead of being enhanced. Excellent potatoes, though. Course 4: Selection of various cheeses from all over the world - great wine pairing. -Impressive on all counts - selection, taste and portioning. Course 5: Chocolate Soufflé and Deconstructed Vanilla Cheesecake - nice wine pairing, accompanied by 2 Cafe Americanos -Both were very good - neither was excellent. Service, overall, was professional. It didn't hold a candle to French Laundry or Acquerello, where you're treated like your party is all that matters, even when they have never seen you before. Ambiance was nicer here than both FL and Acq. But ultimately, it's the food vs.. value and in this regard, I would have to order it as follows: 1. Acquerello - $400 2. FL - $800 3. GD - $650 That said - thanks to my baby who feeds the best food in the whole world, always!!! -

    1 check-in

    gary danko.  when i was going to college at uc berkeley, we read that gary danko was voted best restaurant in the nation (yep. that was our reaction. what?! in the nation?!).  as a poor college student, my roommates and i could not afford to dine here.  therefore, i decided to put it on my bucket list.  for our two year anniversary, we thought we would take a chance and try to get a reservation!  score! we got one! on a saturday!

    it could be that we were overhyped about this place... or because the restaurant was having a bad day.  our experience at gary dank was somewhat of a letdown. we weren't greeted at all for 15 minutes, our server was barely around to answer any questions (because he was too busy attending to his other tables).  when served, it was abrupt, very short and never with a smile.  we felt bad just asking for more water.  the meal was good but the bad service left a bad taste in our mouths.

    FOOD:  food was good. we recommend the (i) risotto with lobster, rock shrimp, shimeji mushrooms, asparagus and peas (not pictured) and (ii) warm louisiana butter cake with apples, huckleberry sauce and vanilla bean ice cream.  those were the two dishes that stood out from the rest.

    SERVICE:  lackluster.  didn't seem to want to serve us at all.

    AMBIENCE:  dark. could be a nice date place.

    OVERALL:  i wish we could say better things about this place but we would probably never come back.  that's too bad given that they did win best restaurant of the year back in the day.  for the price you pay for your meal, i would expect a lot more from gary danko... but that's just me.

    5/11/2010

    20 photos

    As good as advertised.  Reservations can be hard to come by so plan them weeks, if not months, in advance (especially if you plan to go on the weekend).  Obviously, if you come to Danko, be prepared to splurge.  It's worth it though.  If traveling by car, valet is available in front of the restaurant entrance on North Point or you can find street parking on any of the neighboring streets.

    The restaurant is small to medium sized and can seat 68 people at a given time.  The main rooms can seat up to 6.  There is a private room in the back that can seat up to 10.  There are two private, spacious and well-decorated, unisex restrooms complete with soothing Indian sitar music.  The interior of the restaurant is dark and can get a little loud when everyone's talking.

    There are many servers, all of whom are well-spoken and knowledgeable as to all the menu options and the ingredients and preparation behind them.  They are all dressed in suits with Gary Danko lapel pins.  All of them make you feel very welcome to dine here.

    The menu is prix fixe, but it is very flexible.  You have a choice of three, four, or five course meals from a variety of categories including appetizers, fish and seafood, meat and game birds, cheese, and dessert.  It's flexible because you can choose as many from each category as you'd like.  So you can go with five appetizers or five dessert items if you want.  They do ask that your party submit the entire order at one time so they get the timing of all your dishes and courses right.  Also, the total amount of food served is the same, no matter if you order the three course or the five course.  This means that portion sizes of each course are adjusted accordingly.

    Among the items ordered when we went (be sure to check out my Local Photos for pictures of most of the items listed below):

    Asparagus salad with quail eggs, prosciutto and red-onion caper vinaigrette.
    Dungeness crab salad with avocado mousse, pineapple, hearts of palm and curry-lemon vinaigrette.
    Lobster and fennel bisque with dungeness crab, peppers and saffron-orange remoulade.
    Glazed oysters with Osetra caviar, zucchini pearls and lettuce cream.
    Prosciutto wrapped bluenose bass with lentils, parsley, royal trumpet mushrooms, and fava beans.
    Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, carrot-ginger puree and vanilla poached rhubarb.
    Braised lamb shoulder and herb crusted loin with barley stew, red pepper relish and cumin yogurt.
    Quail stuffed with foie gras, mushrooms and quinoa, artichokes, olives and scallion-potato cake.
    Flambeed pineapple with coconut-macadamia dacquoise and rum-coconut sorbet prepared tableside.
    Strawberry dumplings with braised rhubarb and creme fraiche ice cream.
    Baked chocolate souffle with two sauces.

    There was also an amuse-bouche of spring onion bisque with a bread dumpling to start.  At the end of the meal, the dessert also came along with a sample of various sweet dessert bites and a take-home pineapple and blueberry cheese breakfast cake (for ladies only).  Very nice.  All of the food was superb and lived up to the billing.

    There were a lot of nice touches to the dinner.  For example, the bowl for the lobster and fennel bisque was pre-heated and the bisque was poured out of a small pot into the bowl at the table.  The flambeed pineapple was also fun to watch being prepared tableside as you could see the sugar and cream being caramelized right in front of your eyes.  Overall, Gary Danko was a great fine dining experience and I highly recommend it!

    9/11/2009

    16 photos

    ROTD 11/2/2009

    I don't consider myself particularly luckier than the average person in most regards.
    But one way in which I have extraordinary luck is food:  I have eaten at some of the best eateries in existence, on the planet.

    In one way, this makes my reviews more diverse and accurate.  In another way, this makes a 5-star rating from me impossible to attain.

    The last two reviews have been about birthday dinners for me.  Number 3 was a place where we basically pay the rent, Shabu House.  For #4 - enter Gary Danko (herein referred to as "GD").  This iconic establishment in San Francisco is constantly mentioned in the same sentence as the well-known French Laundry - people always preferring one over the other.  Having frequented Thomas Keller's restaurants often - I was excited to try Gary Danko, where Rob had secured reservations for my actual birthdate evening.  I was curious which I would end up preferring.  Furthermore, GD was going to be compared to MY favorite SF dining establishment - Acquerello, as well.

    We arrived right on time, and the hostess asked if we had a reservation.  Rob pointed to his name on the book, and we both noticed she immediately covered up the book - as if we were going to just point to a name and be seated, somehow omniscient to the fact that this particular party wouldn't show up in 2 minutes to boot us out?  It was rude and inappropriate.

    However, she didn't ask for I.D. and seated us immediately.

    First, I was taken aback by how large the restaurant is.  The ambiance is warm and very inviting, and the seating is very comfortable.  With plenty of people waiting near the bar in hopes of being seated, plenty more were seated at the bar eating dinner there.

    Our server approached us, explained their menu, and asked if we'd like to start with drinks.  We ordered a half bottle of champagne, because we knew we'd be doing the wine pairing for dinner.  Rob ordered an ounce of the caviar ($125) to go w/ the champagne, which was excellent - great crème fraiche with the world's best bellinis - so full of butter I could FEEL myself gaining weight with each bite.  Both of us opted for 5 courses.  What stood out about the GD menu is that one can pick all five courses from any section.  If you pick 5 main entrees, they will adjust portioning accordingly and serve it to you - or you could pick 5 desserts, for all they care.  FL has a set menu, and Acquerello, you can pick one from each designated course.

    As usual, I have uploaded photos of the dinner courses.  
    Rob opted for individual five courses, I chose the 5-course Summer Tasting Menu.  After an amuse bouche -  the meal began.  

    Course 1:
    Ahi Tuna (Rob's) and Oysters w/ Caviar (mine, from the Summer Menu) - excellent wine pairing, with sake for the tuna.
    - I consider seared Ahi to be boring.  Now I know that even Gary himself cannot do much to make this fish interesting.
    - LET IT BE SAID:  THIS WAS THE FINEST OYSTER APPETIZER I HAVE EVER HAD IN MY ENTIRE LIFE.  (Specifically, my comment was:  "Move over, Thomas - I think I just fell in love w/ Gary Danko.")

    Course 2:
    Lobster Salad and Crusted Salmon - excellent wine pairing.
    - The lobster was good overall, but I have had better.  I didn't think the dish itself was very flavorful.
    -  LET IT BE SAID:  THIS WAS THE BEST SALMON CREATION EVER.  More than the salmon itself, how the flavors in this dish - the fish, the cucumbers, the horseradish, sauce, crust  - was simply invigorating.  (I envisioned Acquerello, sinking before my eyes....)

    Course 3:  
    Pork Loin and Belly - Beef Filet - mediocre wine pairing.
    *This, along with the hostess episode, is where Gary Danko begins to remind me of  the Titanic.*
    - Pork was unimpressive all around.  The pork loin was dry and weak in taste, the pork belly was unremarkable in every way.  (How does one ruin pork belly?)
    - Beef Filet - the meat was of excellent quality, it was a tad overcooked than I would have liked for this cut of meat, and the flavor of the meat ended up being masked by the sauces instead of being enhanced.  Excellent potatoes, though.

    Course 4:
    Selection of various cheeses from all over the world - great wine pairing.
    -Impressive on all counts - selection, taste and portioning.

    Course 5:
    Chocolate Soufflé and Deconstructed Vanilla Cheesecake - nice wine pairing, accompanied by 2 Cafe Americanos
    -Both were very good - neither was excellent.  

    Service, overall, was professional.  It didn't hold a candle to French Laundry or Acquerello, where you're treated like your party is all that matters, even when they have never seen you before.
    Ambiance was nicer here than both FL and Acq.

    But ultimately, it's the food vs.. value and in this regard, I would have to order it as follows:

    1.  Acquerello - $400
    2.  FL - $800
    3.  GD - $650

    That said - thanks to my baby who feeds the best food in the whole world, always!!!


    -

    My 10th Michelin Star!

    This is my 6th single star restaurant and it was one of the better ones. My parents took Yuko and I here for our engagement present and what a delicious present it was!

    We were able to snag a private dining room for the six of us and it couldn't have been better. The service was top notch and very attentive. We were quickly brought out an amuse bouche of carrot and ginger soup with lobster and cream. It was only a few bites but it was great! Perfectly cooked lobster and the soup was light and full of flavor.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    Since my sister was running late we decided to get caviar service to kill some time. You know, one of those, "I'm bored, let's eat an ounce of caviar for $95 to kill time" moments.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    The caviar was served with the best blini I've ever had. They were hot, slightly crisp, buckwheat pancakes that masterfully offset the caviar and crème fresh. I could have had they entire caviar service for myself.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    The caviar itself was noticeably superior than what is normally dollopped atop a normal dish. This was fresh and clean tasting and not overly salty. I could have eaten the whole jar to myself. Later I found out that the brand of caviar we had retails for $75 an ounce and GD only marked it up $20, pretty sweet deal considering the service and blini extras.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    Two of us had the five course meal and the other four had the four course meal. Between us, we tacked a large chunk of the menu. For my first course, I had to get the Sonoma foie gras. Served with caramelized red onions and rhubarb it was up there with the best foie I've had. Flawlessly seared and perfectly cooked, it was fantastic. The foie melted in my mouth and I could hear myself getting fatter.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    The girl got a tuna salad that came with avocado, nori, and some mushrooms. I had a few bites and it was much better than the tuna entre I got for myself.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    My pan seared tuna with piperade, artichokes, white anchovies, and caper berries was the low point of my meal. It was good but had no "wow" factor for me. The tuna was cooked too much for me and the veggies didn't pop with any spectacular flavor.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    For the meat course, the girl got the lamb and damn it was good! Impeccably cooked and rolled in herbs, this lamb was divine. The spring onions that it came with were some of the best veggies of the night.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    What's better than tiny, cute birds cooked to perfection? Tiny, cute birds stuffed with force fed duck liver! My meat dish was the foie gras stuffed quail and it was a tiny package of extraordinary flavors! The skin and drumsticks of this little bird were enough to satisfy me.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    But once I disemboweled that lil' guy, I knew I was in for a real treat. As soon as I opened him up, foie gras, leeks, mushroom, etc., all started spilling out like a bad (but great) horror movie. Truly delicious.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    Next was the cheese plate. Since we were upstairs, we didn't get the entertainment package known as the cheese cart, but our waitress did a great job meeting the varied needs of the three of us who had cheese. I can't recall at all what she picked for me, but I loved them all.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    For dessert, I put GD to the ultimate test, crème brûlée. It's been years since I've had an undoubtedly great crème brûlée. GD did not disappoint, the top layer was thin, warm, and shattered with the tap of my spoon. But the two little "cookies" that came on my plate almost stole the show! I have no idea what they were but they were amazing!
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    The meal as a whole was fantastic. And at $95 for the five courses, it really is a good value as well. Even the menus were personalized, congratulating us on our engagement. We were also given an extra dessert to help celebrate. It was some sort of lemon "ice cream" or frozen mousse, but whatever it was, it was the best dessert of the night.
    yelp.com/biz_photos/Wavv…

    Gary Danko did not fail in the slightest to impress.
